# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bering-sea
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Due to harsh winds, frequent cloud cover, and cold temperatures, vegetation is mostly tundra (grasses, mosses, berries, low-lying flowering plants) at lower elevations.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The highest point is Mount Moffett, near the northwest end of the island, at an elevation of 3,924 feet (1,196 m).
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] It is snow covered the greater part of the year.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The word *Adak* is from the Aleut word *adaq*, which means "father".
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak Island has been the home to Aleut peoples since antiquity.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Russian explorers in the 18th century also visited the island but made no permanent settlements.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] During World War II, the Imperial Japanese Army took control of two of the westernmost Aleutian Islands, Attu and Kiska, in the incorporated territory of Alaska, the first foreign enemy to occupy American soil since the War of 1812.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The Japanese also attacked the American base at Dutch Harbor by air.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The Japanese campaign coincided with the more well-known Battle of Midway.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] In response, the United States military began a campaign to oust the Japanese.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Since the nearest U.S. military presence was in Cold Bay, Alaska, the U.S. began to construct bases in the western Aleutian Islands from which to launch operations against the Japanese.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak Island was chosen as the site of an airfield, and flight operations began in September 1942.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] On May 11, 1943, four days after the initial invasion date was delayed by bad weather, American soldiers landed on Attu Island and defeated the Japanese garrison there, at the cost of 2,300 Japanese and 550 American lives.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Expecting a similar battle for Kiska Island, U.S. and Allied soldiers landing there August 15, 1943, found the occupiers had been stealthily evacuated by Japanese naval forces since the end of May, 1943.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Even so, over 313 Allied soldiers died from friendly fire, mines, and other anti-personnel devices during Allied operations to take back Kiska.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] In 1953, remains of 236 Japanese dead who had been buried in Adak Cemetery were reburied in Japan's Chidorigafuchi National Cemetery.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] After the war was over, some of the approximately 6,000 American military men who served on Adak during World War II recalled Adak's cold, foggy, windy weather; mud; Quonset huts; few women and no trees; and a volcano that from time to time would issue puffs of smoke.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak Naval Air Station continued to be a military base during the Cold War but was designated a Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC) site in 1995 and closed in March 1997.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Shortly thereafter, the town of Adak was incorporated at the site of the former base.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Down from a peak population of 6,000, the island recorded a 2020 census population of 171 residents, all in the city of Adak, in the northern part of the island.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] In 1980, the Aleutian Islands National Wildlife Refuge was created and much of Adak Island lies within its boundaries.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The Alaska Department of Fish and Game introduced approximately 23 caribou calves to the island in the late 1950s, in part to help prevent famine emergencies.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak Island, with its now large caribou herd of approximately 1,000 animals, according to a 2019 and 2022 count, has become a popular hunting destination.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak has a subpolar oceanic climate (Koppen Cfc), characterized by persistently overcast skies, moderated temperatures, high winds, significant precipitation and frequent cyclonic storms.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] At Adak, overcast conditions average nearly 75 percent of the time during June and July, dropping back to approximately 50 percent of the time from October through February.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak averages 173 days per year with fog.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The foggiest months are July and August, when an average of 26 of the 31 days have fog.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] This number drops dramatically toward the winter season, where the months of December through March have, on average, fewer than ten days with fog during any one month.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Gales occur in all months of the year at Adak, with the greatest chances being from December through March.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] A peak gust of 109 knots (202 km/h; 125 mph) occurred at Adak in March 1954.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak's average temperatures range from 20 to 60 °F (−7 to 16 °C), with a record high of 75 °F (24 °C) in August 1956 and a record low of 3 °F (−16 °C) in January 1963 and February 1964.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Average annual precipitation is about 54.8 inches (1,390 mm).
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] October to January are the wettest months due to especially frequent and intense mid-latitude cyclonic storms, while May to July represent markedly drier months; thunderstorms, common in mid-latitude continental areas, are virtually unknown here.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] November is the average wettest month, while July is the average driest month.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Average snowfall is 100 inches (2,500 mm), falling primarily on the upper reaches of the volcanoes.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak has an average of 341 days per year with measurable precipitation.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak is served by the Aleutian Region Schools.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The Adak School, now closed due to declining enrollment, used to serve grades K–12 and had around 20 students before it was officially shuttered on June 30, 2023.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] A land exchange between Alaska Native Regional Corporations, the U.S.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Navy, and the Department of the Interior has transferred most of the naval facilities to the Aleut Corp.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] A portion of the Island will remain within the National Maritime National Wildlife Refuge, managed by U.S.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak currently provides a fueling port and crew transfer facility for foreign fishing fleets—an airport, docks, housing facilities and food services are available.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] A grocery and ship supply store and restaurant opened in February 1999.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Aleut Corporation maintains the facilities.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Contractors are performing an environmental clean-up.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Alaskan-owned Norquest-Adak Seafood Co. processes Pacific cod, pollock, mackerel, halibut, albacore and brown king crab.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Four residents hold a commercial fishing permit, primarily for groundfish.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] In 2022, Netflix aired a docuseries about explorers seeking pirate gold on the island.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Because of its naval aviation past, Adak has an unusually large and sophisticated airport for the Aleutian Islands.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The Adak Airport is operated by the State of Alaska Department of Transportation.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak Airport has a control tower, an Instrument Landing System and two runways; 7,790 ft (2,370 m) and 7,605 ft (2,318 m) respectively.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Both runways are asphalt paved, 200 ft (61 m) wide and at an elevation of 19 ft (6 m).
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Alaska Airlines operates twice-weekly Boeing 737-800 passenger and cargo jet service from Anchorage.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] At present, flights operate each Wednesday and Saturday (weather permitting).
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Occasionally, extra seasonal flights are operated to meet the demand of the fishing season.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak Airport was historically served for many years by Reeve Aleutian Airways (RAA), with scheduled passenger flights to Anchorage operated with Lockheed L-188 Electra turboprop combi aircraft during the 1970s, followed by Boeing 727-100 jet combi aircraft during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Other facilities in Adak include three deep water docks and fueling facilities.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] There are approximately 16 miles (26 km) of paved and primitive roads on Adak, all privately owned by the Aleut Corporation.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The Aleutian shield fern is an endangered species found only on this island.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adak National Forest is a small copse on the island jokingly referred to as a national forest.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] Adagdak and Mount Moffett volcanoes are located on Adak.
[src:bering-sea/adak-island] The igneous rock type adakite is named after Adak.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The **Adriatic Sea** (/ˌeɪdriˈætɪk/) is a body of water separating the Italian Peninsula from the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic is the northernmost arm of the Mediterranean Sea, extending from the Strait of Otranto (where it connects to the Ionian Sea) to the northwest and the Po Valley.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The countries with coasts on the Adriatic are Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Italy, Montenegro, and Slovenia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic contains more than 1,300 islands, mostly located along its eastern coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It is divided into three basins, the northern being the shallowest and the southern being the deepest, with a maximum depth of 1,233 metres (4,045 ft).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The prevailing currents flow counterclockwise from the Strait of Otranto.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Tidal movements in the Adriatic are slight, although larger amplitudes occur occasionally.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's salinity is lower than the Mediterranean's because it collects a third of the fresh water flowing into the Mediterranean, acting as a dilution basin.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The surface water temperatures generally range from 30 °C (86 °F) in summer to 12 °C (54 °F) in winter, significantly moderating the Adriatic Basin's climate.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea sits on the Apulian or Adriatic Microplate.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the Italian Peninsula first formed, separating the Adriatic Basin from the rest of the Mediterranean.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The western coast is alluvial or terraced, while the eastern coast is highly indented with pronounced karstification.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] There are dozens of marine protected areas in the Adriatic, designed to protect the sea's habitats and biodiversity—more than 7,000 species are identified as native to the Adriatic, many of them endemic, rare and threatened ones.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's shores are populated by more than 3.5 million people; the largest cities are Bari, Venice, Trieste and Split.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Early settlements on the Adriatic shores were Etruscan, Illyrian, and Greek.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] By the 2nd century BC, the region was under Rome's control.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Middle Ages, the sea was controlled, to a varying extent, by a series of states—most notably the Byzantine Empire, the Croatian Kingdom, the Republic of Venice, the Habsburg monarchy and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Napoleonic Wars resulted in the Austrian Empire gaining control of most of the eastern Adriatic shore and the Po Valley, while the Kingdom of Italy gradually took control of the remaining Italian coast during the 19th century.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Following the collapse of Austria-Hungary in 1918, control of the eastern coast passed to Yugoslavia and Albania, which agreed on their maritime boundaries with Italy in 1975 and 1992 respectively.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] After Yugoslavia's dissolution during the 1990s, its four coastal successor states—Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro—continued to recognise the previous maritime border with Italy, but have disputed the borders between themselves.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Fisheries and tourism are significant sources of income along the Adriatic coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Maritime transport is also a significant branch of the area's economy—there are 19 seaports in the Adriatic that each handle more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The largest Adriatic seaport by annual cargo turnover is the Port of Trieste, while the Port of Split is the largest by passengers served per year.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The origins of the name *Adriatic* are linked to the Etruscan settlement of Adria, which probably derives its name from Illyrian *adur* 'water, sea'.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In classical antiquity, the sea was known as *Mare Adriaticum* (*Mare Hadriaticum*, also sometimes simplified to *Adria*) or, less frequently, as *Mare Superum* '[the] upper sea'.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The two terms were not synonymous, however.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] *Mare Adriaticum* generally corresponds to the Adriatic Sea's extent, spanning from the Gulf of Venice to the Strait of Otranto.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] That boundary became more consistently defined by Roman authors—early Greek sources place the boundary between the Adriatic and Ionian seas at various places ranging from adjacent to the Gulf of Venice to the southern tip of the Peloponnese, eastern shores of Sicily and western shores of Crete.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] *Mare Superum* on the other hand normally encompassed both the modern Adriatic Sea and the sea off the Apennine peninsula's southern coast, as far as the Strait of Sicily.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Another name used in the period was *Mare Dalmaticum*, applied to waters off the coast of Dalmatia or Illyricum.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] During the early modern period, the entire sea was also known as the **Gulf of Venice** (Italian: *golfo di Venezia*), although that name is now informally applied only to the northern area of the sea, from Maestra Point in the Po Delta to Cape Kamenjak on the Istrian Peninsula.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In Serbo-Croatian and Slovene, the sea is often referred to as simply *Jadran*.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a semi-enclosed sea, bordered in the southwest by the Apennine or Italian Peninsula, in the northwest by the Italian regions of Veneto and Friuli-Venezia Giulia, and in the northeast by Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, and Albania—the Balkan peninsula.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the southeast, the Adriatic Sea connects to the Ionian Sea at the 72-kilometre (45 mi) wide Strait of Otranto.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It extends 800 kilometres (500 mi) from the northwest to the southeast and is 200 kilometres (120 mi) wide.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It covers 138,600 square kilometres (53,500 sq mi) and has a volume of 35,000 cubic kilometres (8,400 cu mi).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic extends northwest from 40° to 45°47' north, representing the Mediterranean's northernmost portion.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The sea is geographically divided into the Northern Adriatic, Central (or Middle) Adriatic, and Southern Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea drainage basin encompasses 235,000 square kilometres (91,000 sq mi), yielding a land–sea ratio of 1.8.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The drainage basin's mean elevation is 782 metres (2,566 ft) above sea level, with a mean slope of 12.1°.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Major rivers discharging into the Adriatic include the Po, Soča, Krka, Neretva, Drin, Buna, and Vjosë.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the late 19th century, Austria-Hungary established a geodetic network with an elevation benchmark using the average Adriatic Sea level at the Sartorio pier in Trieste, Italy.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The benchmark was subsequently retained by Austria, adopted by Yugoslavia, and retained by the states that emerged after its dissolution.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In 2016, Slovenia adopted a new elevation benchmark referring to the upgraded tide gauge station in the coastal town of Koper.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Alps, which also have a large meteorological impact on the Mediterranean, touch the Adriatic in the area around Trieste towards Duino and Barcola.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea contains more than 1,300 islands and islets, most along the Adriatic's eastern coast—especially in Croatia, with 1,246 counted.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The number includes islands, islets, and rocks of all sizes, including ones emerging at ebb tide only.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian islands include the largest—Cres and Krk, each covering about the same area of 405.78 square kilometres (156.67 sq mi)—and the tallest—Brač, whose peak reaches 780 metres (2,560 ft) above sea level.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The islands of Cres and the adjacent Lošinj are separated only by a narrow navigable canal dug in the time of classical antiquity; the original single island was known to the Greeks as Apsyrtides.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian islands include 47 permanently inhabited ones, the most populous among them being Krk, Korčula and Brač.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The islands along the Adriatic's western (Italian) coast are smaller and less numerous than those along the opposite coast; the best-known ones are the 117 islands on which the city of Venice is built.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The northern shore of the Greek island of Corfu also lies in the Adriatic Sea as defined by the IHO.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The IHO boundary places the Diapontia Islands (northwest of Corfu) in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea's average depth is 259.5 metres (851 ft), and its maximum depth is 1,233 metres (4,045 ft); however, the North Adriatic basin rarely exceeds a depth of 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The North Adriatic basin, extending between Venice and Trieste towards a line connecting Ancona and Zadar, is only 15 metres (49 ft) deep at its northwestern end; it gradually deepens towards the southeast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It is the largest Mediterranean shelf and is simultaneously a dilution basin and a site of bottom water formation.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Middle Adriatic basin is south of the Ancona–Zadar line, with the 270-metre (890 ft) deep Middle Adriatic Pit (also called the Pomo Depression or the Jabuka Pit).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The 170-metre (560 ft) deep Palagruža Sill is south of the Middle Adriatic Pit, separating it from the 1,200-metre (3,900 ft) deep South Adriatic Pit and the Middle Adriatic basin from the South Adriatic Basin.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Further on to the south, the sea floor rises to 780 metres (2,560 ft) to form the Otranto Sill at the boundary to the Ionian Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The South Adriatic Basin is similar in many respects to the Northern Ionian Sea, to which it is connected.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The coast's ruggedness is exacerbated by the Dinaric Alps' proximity to the coast, in contrast to the opposite (Italian) coast where the Apennine Mountains are further away from the shoreline.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The coastal water dynamics are determined by the asymmetric coasts and the inflow of the Mediterranean seawater through the Straits of Otranto and further on along the eastern coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The smooth Italian coast (with very few protrusions and no major islands) allows the Western Adriatic Current, which is composed of the relatively freshwater mass on the surface and the cold and dense water mass at the bottom, to flow smoothly.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The coastal currents on the opposite shore are far more complex owing to the jagged shoreline, several large islands and the proximity of the Dinaric Alps to the shore.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The last produces significant temperature variations between the sea and the hinterland, which leads to the creation of local jets.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The tidal movement is normally slight, usually remaining below 30 centimetres (12 in).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The amphidromic point is at the mid-width east of Ancona.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The normal tide levels are known to increase significantly in a conducive environment, leading to coastal flooding; this phenomenon is most famously known in Italy—especially Venice—as *acqua alta*.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Such tides can exceed normal levels by more than 140 centimetres (55 in), with the highest tide level of 194 centimetres (76 in) observed on 4 November 1966.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Such flooding is caused by a combination of factors, including the alignment of the Sun and Moon, meteorological factors such as sirocco related storm surges, and the basin's geometric shape (which amplifies or reduces the astronomical component).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Moreover, the Adriatic's long and narrow rectangular shape is the source of an oscillating water motion (French: *seiche*) along the basin's minor axis.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Finally, Venice is increasingly vulnerable to flooding due to coastal area soil subsidence.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Such unusually high tides resulting in flooding have also been observed elsewhere in the Adriatic Sea, and have been recorded in recent years in the towns of Koper, Zadar and Šibenik as well.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that the Adriatic's entire volume is exchanged through the Strait of Otranto in 3.4±0.4 years, a comparatively short period.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] (For instance, approximately 500 years are necessary to exchange all the Black Sea's water.) This short period is particularly important as the rivers flowing into the Adriatic discharge up to 5,700 cubic metres per second (200,000 cu ft/s).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] This rate of discharge amounts to 0.5% of the total Adriatic Sea volume, or a 1.3-metre (4 ft 3 in) layer of water each year.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The greatest portion of the discharge from any single river comes from the Po (28%), with an average discharge from it alone of 1,569 cubic metres per second (55,400 cu ft/s).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In terms of the annual total discharge into the entire Mediterranean Sea, the Po is ranked second, followed by the Neretva and Drin, which rank as third and fourth.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Another significant contributor of freshwater to the Adriatic is the submarine groundwater discharge through submarine springs (Croatian: *vrulja*); it is estimated to comprise 29% of the total water flux into the Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The submarine springs include thermal springs, discovered offshore near the town of Izola.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The thermal spring water is rich with hydrogen sulfide, has a temperature of 22 to 29.6 °C (71.6 to 85.3 °F), and has enabled the development of specific ecosystems.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The inflow of freshwater, representing a third of the freshwater volume flowing into the Mediterranean, makes the Adriatic a dilution basin for the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Middle and South Adriatic Gyres (SAG), are significant cyclonic circulation features, with the former being intermittent and the latter permanent.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The SAG measures 150 kilometres (93 miles) in diameter.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It contributes to the flow of bottom water from the Adriatic to the Levantine Basin through the Ionian Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Through that process, the Adriatic Sea produces most of the East Mediterranean deep water.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's surface temperature usually ranges from 22 to 30 °C (72 to 86 °F) in the summer, or 12 to 14 °C (54 to 57 °F) in the winter, except along the western Adriatic coast's northern part, where it drops to 9 °C (48 °F) in the winter.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The distinct seasonal temperature variations, with a longitudinal gradient in the Northern and transversal gradient in the Middle and Southern Adriatic, are attributed to the continental characteristics of the Adriatic Sea: it is shallower and closer to land than are oceans.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] During particularly cold winters, sea ice may appear in the Adriatic's shallow coastal areas, especially in the Venetian Lagoon but also in isolated shallows as far south as Tisno (south of Zadar).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Southern Adriatic is about 8 to 10 °C (14 to 18 °F) warmer during the winter than the more northerly regions.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's salinity variation over the year is likewise distinct: it ranges between 38 and 39 PSUs, somewhat higher than the range of 32 to 37 PSUs for the open ocean.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The southern Adriatic is subjected to saltier water from the Levantine Basin.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, the upper half of the Adriatic is classified as humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*), with wetter summers and colder and drier winters, and the southern Adriatic are classified as hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The air temperature can fluctuate by about 20 °C (36 °F) during a season.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The predominant winter winds are the bora and sirocco (called *jugo* along the eastern coast).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The bora is significantly conditioned by wind gaps in the Dinaric Alps bringing cold and dry continental air; it reaches peak speeds in the areas of Trieste, Senj, and Split, with gusts of up to 180 kilometres per hour (97 kn; 110 mph).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The sirocco brings humid and warm air, often carrying Saharan sand causing rain dust.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] On the Adriatic Sea's coasts and islands, there are numerous small settlements and a number of larger cities.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Among the largest are (counterclockwise) Trieste, Venice, Rimini, Ancona, Pescara and Bari in Italy; Vlorë and Durrës in Albania; Split, Zadar and Rijeka in Croatia; Koper in Slovenia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In total, more than 3.5 million people live on the Adriatic coasts.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] There are also some larger cities that are located very near the coast, such as the Italian cities of Ravenna and Lecce.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Venice, which was originally built on islands off the coast, is most at risk due to subsidence, but the threat is present in the Po delta as well.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The causes are a decrease in sedimentation rate due to loss of sediment behind dams, the deliberate excavation of sand for industrial purposes, agricultural use of water, and removal of ground water.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The sinking of Venice slowed after artesian wells were banned in the 1960s, but the city remains threatened by the *acqua alta* floods.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Recent studies have suggested that the city is no longer sinking, but a state of alert remains in place.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In May 2003, then-Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi inaugurated the MOSE project (Italian: *Modulo Sperimentale Elettromeccanico*), an experimental model for evaluating the performance of inflatable gates.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The project proposes laying a series of 79 inflatable pontoons across the sea bed at the three entrances to the Venetian Lagoon.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] When tides are predicted to rise above 110 centimetres (43 in), the pontoons will be filled with air and block the incoming water from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] This engineering work was due to be completed by 2014, but as of November 2020 is expected to be completed in 2021.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] However, concern has been raised regarding the frequency of its use—while only necessary a few days a year, the worst-case sea level rise scenario between 2050 and 2100 would prompt deployment up to 187 days a year, essentially cutting off the Venetian Lagoon from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Among other possible adverse effects, this can be expected to lower the lagoon's oxygen levels and trap pollution inside of the city.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Geophysical and geological information indicate that the Adriatic Sea and the Po Valley are associated with a tectonic microplate—identified as the Apulian or Adriatic Plate—that separated from the African Plate during the Mesozoic era.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] This separation began in the Middle and Late Triassic, when limestone began to be deposited in the area.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Between the Norian and Late Cretaceous, the Adriatic and Apulia Carbonate Platforms formed as a thick series of carbonate sediments (dolomites and limestones), up to 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) deep.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Remnants of the former are found in the Adriatic Sea, as well as in the southern Alps and the Dinaric Alps, and remnants of the latter are seen as the Gargano Promontory and the Maiella mountain.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Eocene and early Oligocene, the plate moved north and north-east, contributing to the Alpine orogeny (along with the African and Eurasian Plates' movements) via the tectonic uplift of the Dinarides and Alps.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the motion was reversed and the Apennine Mountains' orogeny took place.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] An unbroken zone of increased seismic activity borders the Adriatic Sea, with a belt of thrust faults generally oriented in the northeast–southwest direction on the east coast and the northeast–southwest normal faults in the Apennines, indicating an Adriatic counterclockwise rotation.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] An active 200-kilometre (120 mi) fault has been identified to the northwest of Dubrovnik, adding to the Dalmatian islands as the Eurasian Plate slides over the Adriatic microplate.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Furthermore, the fault causes the Apennine peninsula's southern tip to move towards the opposite shore by about 0.4 centimetres (0.16 in) per year.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] If this movement continues, the seafloor will be completely consumed and the Adriatic Sea closed off in 50–70 million years.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Northern Adriatic, the coast of the Gulf of Trieste and western Istria is gradually subsiding, having sunk about 1.5 metres (4 ft 11 in) in the past two thousand years.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Middle Adriatic Basin, there is evidence of Permian volcanism in the area of Komiža on the island of Vis and the volcanic islands of Jabuka and Brusnik.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Earthquakes have been observed in the region since the earliest historical records.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] A recent strong earthquake in the region was the 1979 Montenegro earthquake, measuring 7.0 on the Richter scale.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Historical earthquakes in the area include the 1627 Gargano peninsula and the 1667 Dubrovnik earthquakes, both followed by strong tsunamis.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the last 600 years, fifteen tsunamis have occurred in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] All types of seafloor sediments are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Northern Adriatic's comparatively shallow seabed is characterised by relict sand (from times when the water level was lower and the area was a sandy beach), while a muddy bed is typical at depths below 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Sediments deposited in the Adriatic Sea today generally come from the northwest coast, being carried by the Po, Reno, Adige, Brenta, Tagliamento, Piave and Soča rivers.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The volume of sediments carried from the eastern shore by the Rječina, Zrmanja, Krka, Cetina, Ombla, Dragonja, Mirna, Raša and Neretva rivers is negligible, because these sediments are mostly deposited at the river mouths.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's western shores are largely either alluvial or terraced, whereas the eastern shores are predominantly rocky, except for the southernmost part of the shore located in Albania that consists of sandy coves and rocky capes.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The eastern Adriatic shore's Croatian part is the most indented Mediterranean coastline.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Most of the eastern coast is characterised by a karst topography, developed from the Adriatic Carbonate Platform's exposure to weathering.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Karstification there largely began after the Dinarides' final uplift in the Oligocene and the Miocene, when carbonate deposits were exposed to atmospheric effects; this extended to the level of 120 metres (390 ft) below the present sea level, exposed during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that some karst formations are from earlier sea level drops, most notably the Messinian salinity crisis.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Similarly, karst developed in Apulia from the Apulian Carbonate Platform.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Rocks of the same type are found in Albania and on the western Adriatic coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] There are alternations of maritime and alluvial sediments occurring in the Po Valley, at the Adriatic's north-west coast, and as far west as Piacenza, dating to the Pleistocene as the sea advanced and receded over the valley.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] An advance began after the Last Glacial Maximum, which brought the Adriatic to a high point at about 5,500 years ago.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Since then, the Po delta has been prograding (expanding/extending).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The rate of coastal zone progradation between 1000 BC and 1200 AD was 4 metres (13 ft) per year.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the 12th century, the delta advanced at a rate of 25 metres (82 ft) per year.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the 17th century, the delta began to become a human-controlled environment, as the excavation of artificial channels started; the channels and new distributaries of the Po have been prograding at rates of 50 metres (160 ft) per year or more since then.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] There are more than 20 other rivers flowing into the Adriatic Sea in Italy alone, also forming alluvial coastlines, including the lagoons of Venice, Grado and Caorle.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] There are smaller eastern Adriatic alluvial coasts—in the deltas of the Dragonja, Buna and Neretva rivers.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a unique water body in respect of its overall biogeochemical physiognomy.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It exports inorganic nutrients and imports particulate organic carbon and nitrogen through the Strait of Otranto—acting as a mineralization site.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The exchange of the substances is made more complex by bathymetry of the Adriatic Sea—75% of water flowing north through the strait recirculates at the Palagruža Sill and North Adriatic adds no more than 3–4% of water to the South Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] This is reflected in its biogeography and ecology, and particularly in the composition and properties of its ecosystems.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Its main biogeographic units are the Northern Adriatic, the Central Adriatic, and the Southern Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The unique nature of the Adriatic gives rise to an abundance of endemic flora and fauna.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian National Biodiversity Strategy Action Plan identified more than 7,000 animal and plant species in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Central Adriatic is especially abundant in endemic plant species, with 535 identified species of green, brown and red algae.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Four out of five Mediterranean seagrass species are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The most common species are *Cymodocea nodosa* and *Zostera noltii*, while *Zostera marina* and *Posidonia oceanica* are comparatively rare.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] This circulation has significantly contributed to the biodiversity of the countries along the eastern Adriatic coast; the common bottlenose dolphin is frequent in the eastern coast's waters only, and the Croatian coast provides refuge for the critically endangered monk seal and sea turtles.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Recent studies revealed that cetaceans and other marine megafaunas, that were once thought to be vagrants to Adriatic Sea, migrate and live in the semi-closed sea on larger scales.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Largest of these live normally is the fin whale, and sperm whale, the largest of toothed whales also migrate but less common than fin whales, followed by Cuvier's beaked whales.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Basking sharks and manta rays are some of migrant species to the sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Historical presences of depleted or extinct species such as North Atlantic right whales (extinct or functionally extinct), Atlantic gray whales (extinct), and humpback whales have been speculated as well.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Tuna has been caught by the locals in the upper Adriatic for thousands of years.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The very large schools consisted mainly of little tunny and moved as far as the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] However, increasing fishing prevented the migration of large schools of fish to the north.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The last major tuna catch was made there in 1954 by the fishermen from Santa Croce, Contovello and Barcola.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Northern Adriatic in particular is rich in endemic fish fauna.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Around thirty species of fish are found in only one or two countries bordering the Adriatic Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] These are particularly due to or dependent upon the karst morphology of the coastal or submarine topography; this includes inhabiting subterranean habitats, karst rivers, and areas around freshwater springs.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] There are 45 known subspecies endemic to the Adriatic's coasts and islands.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Adriatic, there are at least 410 species and subspecies of fish, representing approximately 70% of Mediterranean taxa, with at least 7 species endemic to the Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Sixty-four known species are threatened with extinction, largely because of overfishing.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Only a small fraction of the fish found in the Adriatic are attributed to recent processes such as Lessepsian migration, and escape from mariculture.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The biodiversity of the Adriatic is relatively high, and several marine protected areas have been established by countries along its coasts.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In Italy, these are Miramare in the Gulf of Trieste (in the Northern Adriatic), Torre del Cerrano and Tremiti Islands in the Middle Adriatic basin and Torre Guaceto in southern Apulia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Miramare protected area was established in 1986 and covers 30 hectares (74 acres) of coast and 90 hectares (220 acres) of sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The area encompasses 1.8 kilometres (1.1 mi) of coastline near the Miramare promontory in the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Torre del Cerrano protected area was created in 2009, extending 3 nautical miles (5.6 km; 3.5 mi) into the sea and along 7 kilometres (4.3 mi) of coastline.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Various zones of the protected area cover 37 square kilometres (14 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Tremiti Islands reserve has been protected since 1989, while the Tremiti islands themselves are part of the Gargano National Park.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Torre Guaceto protected area, located near Brindisi and Carovigno, covers a sea surface of 2,227 hectares (5,500 acres) and is adjacent to the Torre Guaceto State Reserve covering 1,114 hectares (2,750 acres) of coast and sharing an 8-kilometre (5.0 mi) coastline with the marine protected area.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Furthermore, there are 10 internationally important (Ramsar) wetland reserves in Italy located along the Adriatic coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Brijuni national park encompasses the 743.3-hectare (1,837-acre) archipelago itself and 2,651.7 hectares (6,552 acres) of surrounding sea; it became a national park in 1999.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Lim Canal is a 10-kilometre (6.2 mi) ria of the Pazinčica river.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Kornati national park was established in 1980; it covers approximately 220 square kilometres (85 sq mi), including 89 islands and islets.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The marine environment encompasses three-quarters of the total area, while the island shores' combined length equals 238 kilometres (148 mi).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Telašćica is a nature park established on Dugi Otok in 1988.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The park covers 69 kilometres (43 mi) of coastline, 22.95 square kilometres (8.86 sq mi) of land and 44.55 square kilometres (17.20 sq mi) of sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Bay of Mali Ston is located at the border of Croatia and Bosnia–Herzegovina, north of the Pelješac peninsula.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The marine protected area covers 48 square kilometres (19 sq mi).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Lastovo nature park was established in 2006, and it includes 44 islands and islets, 53 square kilometres (20 sq mi) of land and 143 square kilometres (55 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Mljet national park was established in 1960, covering a 24-square-kilometre (9.3 sq mi) marine protection area.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In addition, there is a Ramsar wetland reserve in Croatia—the Neretva river's delta.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In Slovenia, the marine and coastal protected nature areas are the Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park, Strunjan Landscape Park, Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve, and the Debeli Rtič, Cape Madona and Lakes in Fiesa natural monuments.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park was established in 1990, covers 721 hectares (1,780 acres), and includes four nature reserves.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In 1993, the area was designated a Ramsar site; it is also a site of international importance for waterbird species.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The 429-hectare (1,060-acre) Strunjan Landscape Park was established in 2004 and comprises two nature reserves.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It includes a 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) long cliff, the northernmost Mediterranean salt field and the only Slovenian lagoon system.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It is also the northernmost point of growth of some Mediterranean plant species.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve was established in 1998 and covers 122 hectares (300 acres).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Debeli Rtič natural monument covers 24 hectares (59 acres), the Cape Madona natural monument covers 12 hectares (30 acres), and the Lakes in Fiesa natural monument, with the coastal lake as the only brackish lake in Slovenia, covers 2.1 hectares (5.2 acres).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In 2010, Albania established its first marine protection area, the Karaburun-Sazan National Marine Park at the Karaburun Peninsula where the Adriatic and Ionian Seas meet.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The park covers a total of 12,570 hectares (31,100 acres).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Two additional marine protection areas are planned in Albania: the Cape of Rodon (Albanian: *Kepi i Rodonit*) and Porto Palermo.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] In addition, Albania is home to two Ramsar wetland reserves: Karavasta Lagoon, and Butrint.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Neither Bosnia–Herzegovina nor Montenegro have or plan to establish any marine protection areas.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea ecosystem is threatened by excessive input of nutrients through drainage from agricultural land and wastewater flowing from cities; this includes both along its coast and from rivers draining into the sea—especially from the Po River.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Venice is often cited as an example of polluted coastal waters where shipping, transportation, farming, manufacturing and wastewater disposal contribute to polluting the sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] A further risk is presented by ballast water discharge by ships, especially tankers.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Still, since most of the cargo handled by the Adriatic ports, and virtually all liquid (tanker) cargo handled by the ports, is coming to—not coming from—the Adriatic Basin, the risk from ballast water (from tankers expelling ballast water then loading in the Adriatic) remains minimal.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] However, proposed export oil pipelines were objected to specifically because of this issue.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Oil spills are a major concern in terms of potential environmental impact and damage to tourism and fisheries.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that if a major oil spill happened, a million people would lose their livelihoods in Croatia alone.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] An additional risk is presented by oil refineries in the Po River basin where oil spills have occurred before, in addition to accidents occurring in the Adriatic already, so far with no significant environmental consequences.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Since 2006, Italy has been considering the construction of an offshore and an onshore LNG terminal in the Gulf of Trieste, as well as a pipeline, in the immediate vicinity of the Slovenian–Italian border.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] The Slovenian government and municipalities, the municipal council of Trieste, and non-governmental organisations have voiced concern over their environmental hazards, effect on transport and effect on tourism.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Another source of pollution of the Adriatic is solid waste.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Drifting waste—occasionally relatively large quantities of material, especially waste plastic—is transported northwest by the sirocco.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Air pollution in the Adriatic Basin is associated with the large industrial centres in the Po River valley and the large industrial cities along the coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Italy and Yugoslavia established a joint commission to protect the Adriatic Sea from pollution in 1977; the organization later changed with Slovenia, Croatia and Montenegro replacing Yugoslavia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] Future pollution hazards are addressed and pollution hotspots are assessed not only by nations in the basin but also through regional projects with World Bank support.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p01] 27 such hotspots have been determined as of 2011, 6 warranting an urgent response.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Settlements along the Adriatic dating to between 6100 and 5900 BC appear in Albania and Dalmatia on the eastern Adriatic coast, related to the Cardium pottery culture.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During classical antiquity, Illyrians inhabited the eastern coast, and the western coast was inhabited by the peoples of Ancient Italy, mainly Etruscans, before the Roman Republic's rise.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Greek colonisation of the Adriatic dates back to the 7th and 6th centuries BC when the ancient cities of Epidamnos and Apollonia were founded.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Greeks soon expanded further north establishing several cities, including Ancona, Black Corcyra, Epidaurus, Issa, with trade established as far north as the Po River delta, where an emporium (trading station) was founded in Adria.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Roman economic and military influence in the region began to grow with the creation by 246 BC of a major naval base at Brundisium (now Brindisi), which was established to bar Carthaginian ships from the Adriatic during the Punic Wars.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] This led to conflict with the Illyrians, who lived in a collection of semi-Hellenized kingdoms that covered much of the Balkans and controlled the eastern shore of the sea, resulting in the Illyrian Wars from 229 to 168 BC.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The initial Roman intervention in 229 BC, motivated in part by a desire to suppress Illyrian piracy in the Adriatic, marked the first time that the Roman navy crossed that sea to launch a military campaign.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Those wars ended with the eastern shore becoming a province of the Roman Republic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] However, resistance to Roman rule continued sporadically and Rome did not completely consolidate control of the region until Augustus's general Tiberius put down the Great Illyrian Revolt, a bitter struggle waged from 6 to 9 AD.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the repression of the revolt the Roman province of Illyricum was split into Dalmatia and Pannonia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During the Roman period, Brundisium, on the western shore, and Apollonia and Dyrrachium (originally called Epidamnos, now Durrës in Albania) on the eastern shore became important ports.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Brundisium was linked by the Via Appia road to the city of Rome, and Dyrrachium and Apollonia were both on the Via Egnatia, a road that by about 130 BC the Romans had extended eastward across the Balkans to Byzantium (later Constantinople, now Istanbul).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] This made the sea passage across the Adriatic between Brundisium and Dyrrachium (or Apollonia) a link in the primary route for travelers, trade, and troop movements, between Rome and the East.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] This route played a major role in some of the military operations that marked the end of the Roman Republic and the start of the imperial period.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Sulla used it during the First Mithridatic War.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Marc Antony and Octavian (later Augustus) crossed the Adriatic to Dyrrachium with their armies in their campaign against two of Caesar's assassins, Brutus and Cassius, that culminated in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Brundisium and Dyrrachium remained important ports well after the Roman period, but an earthquake in the 3rd century AD changed the path of a river causing Apollonia's harbor to silt up, and the city to decline.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Another city on the Italian coast of the Adriatic that increased in importance during the Roman era was Ravenna.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During the reign of Augustus, it became a major naval base as part of his program to re-organize the Roman navy to better protect commerce in the Mediterranean.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During the 4th century AD the emperors of the Western Roman Empire had moved their official residence north from Rome to Mediolanum (now Milan) in order to be better able to control the military frontier with the Germanic tribes.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 402 AD, during a period of repeated Germanic invasions of Italy, the capital was shifted to Ravenna because nearby marshes made it more defensible, and the Adriatic provided an easy escape path by sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] When the Western Empire fell in 476 AD Ravenna became the capital of the Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Early Middle Ages, after the Roman Empire's decline, the Adriatic's coasts were ruled by Ostrogoths, Lombards and the Byzantine Empire.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ostrogothic Kingdom ruled Italy following the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 AD.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] However, during the reign of Justinian the Byzantine Empire sent an army under the general Belisarius to regain control of Italy, resulting in the Gothic War (535–554).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Byzantines established the Exarchate of Ravenna and by 553 AD their viceroy (Exarch) ruled almost the entire Italian peninsula from that city.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 568 AD the Lombards invaded northern Italy, and over the course of the next century or so the importance of the Exarchate declined as the territory under Lombard control expanded and as the Byzantine outpost of Venice became increasingly independent.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 752 AD the Lombards overthrew the Exarchate, ending the influence of the Byzantine Empire on the western shore of the Adriatic for a few centuries.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Republic of Venice, one of the maritime republics, was founded during this period and went on to become a significant maritime power after receiving a Byzantine tax exemption in 1082.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The end of the period brought about the Holy Roman Empire's control over the Kingdom of Italy (which would last until the Peace of Westphalia in 1648), the establishment of an independent Kingdom of Croatia and the Byzantine Empire's return to the southern Apennine peninsula.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In addition, the Papal States were carved out in the area around Rome and central Italy in the 8th century.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In this period, the Republic of Venice began to expand its territory and influence.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1202, the Fourth Crusade was diverted to conquer Zadar at the behest of the Venetians—the first instance of a Crusader force attacking a Catholic city—before proceeding to sack Constantinople.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In the 13th century, Venice established itself as a leading maritime nation.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During much of the 12th and 13th centuries, Venice and the Republic of Genoa were engaged in warfare culminating in the War of Chioggia, ousting the Genoese from the Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Still, the 1381 Treaty of Turin that ended the war required Venice to renounce claims to Dalmatia, after losing the territory to Hungary in 1358.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In the same year, the Republic of Ragusa was established in Dubrovnik as a city-state after it was freed from Venetian suzerainty.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Venice regained Dalmatia in 1409 and held it for nearly four hundred years, with the republic's apex of trading and military power in the first half of the 15th century.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] These defeats spelled the end of an independent Hungarian kingdom, and both Croatian and Hungarian nobility chose Ferdinand I of the House of Habsburg as their new ruler, bringing the Habsburg monarchy to the shore of the Adriatic Sea, where it would remain for nearly four hundred years.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ottomans and Venetians fought a series of wars, but until the 17th century these were not fought in the Adriatic area.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Ottoman raids on the Adriatic coasts effectively ceased after the massive setback in the Battle of Lepanto in October 1571.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The 17th century's final territorial changes were caused by the Morean or Sixth Ottoman–Venetian War, when in 1699 Venice slightly enlarged its possessions in Dalmatia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1797, the Republic of Venice was abolished after the French conquest.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Venetian territory was then handed over to Austria and briefly ruled as part of the Archduchy of Austria.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The territory was turned back over to France after the Peace of Pressburg in 1805 when the territory in the Po valley became an integral part of the new Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The new kingdom included the province of Romagna, thus removing the Papal State from the Adriatic coast; however, Trieste, Istria and Dalmatia were joined into a set of separate provinces of the French Empire: the Illyrian Provinces.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] These were created in 1809 through the Treaty of Schönbrunn; they represented the end of Venetian rule on the eastern Adriatic coast, as well as the end of the Republic of Ragusa.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Sea was a minor theatre in the Napoleonic Wars; the Adriatic campaign of 1807–1814 involved the Royal Navy contesting the Adriatic's control by the combined navies of France, Italy and the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During the campaign, the British navy occupied Vis and established its base there in Port St.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The campaign reached its climax in the 1811 Battle of Lissa, and ended with British and Austrian forces seizing the coastal cities on the eastern Adriatic coast from the French.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Days before the Battle of Waterloo, the Congress of Vienna awarded the Illyrian Provinces (spanning from the Gulf of Trieste to the Bay of Kotor) to Austria.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Congress of Vienna also created the Kingdom of Lombardy–Venetia which encompassed the city of Venice, the surrounding coast and a substantial hinterland, and was controlled by Austria.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Apennine peninsula's south, the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was formed in 1816 by unifying the kingdoms of Naples and Sicily.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The process of Italian unification culminated in the Second Italian War of Independence, resulting in the Kingdom of Sardinia annexing all territories along the western Adriatic coast south of Venetia in 1860, and the 1861 establishment of the Kingdom of Italy in its place.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Kingdom of Italy expanded in 1866: it annexed Venetia, but its navy was defeated in the Adriatic near Vis.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 and the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement of 1868, the control of much of the eastern Adriatic coast was redefined.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The cisleithanian (Austrian) part of Austria-Hungary spanned from the Austrian Littoral to the Bay of Kotor, with the exception of the Croatian Littoral mainland.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In the territory outside the Austrian Littoral, special status was given to Fiume (modern-day Rijeka) as a separate part of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The rest of the territory was made a part of the Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia, which in turn was also in the Transleithanian part of the dual monarchy.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic coastline controlled by the Ottoman Empire was reduced by the Congress of Berlin in 1878, through recognition of the independence of the Principality of Montenegro, which controlled the coast south of the Bay of Kotor to the Bojana River.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ottoman Empire lost all territories along the Adriatic following the First Balkan War and consequent 1913 Treaty of London that established an independent Albania.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The World War I Adriatic Campaign was largely limited to blockade attempts by the Allies and the effort of the Central Powers to thwart the British, French and Italian moves.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Italy joined the Allies in April 1915 with the Treaty of London, which promised Italy the Austrian Littoral, northern Dalmatia, the port of Vlorë, most of the eastern Adriatic islands and Albania as a protectorate.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The treaty provided the basis for all the following divisions between Italy and Yugoslavia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1918, the Montenegrin national assembly voted to unite with the Kingdom of Serbia, giving the latter access to the Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Another short-lived, unrecognised state established in 1918 was the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs, formed from parts of Austria-Hungary, comprising most of the former monarchy's Adriatic coastline.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Later that year, the Kingdom of Serbia and the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs formed the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes—subsequently renamed Yugoslavia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The proponents of the new union in the Croatian parliament saw the move as a safeguard against Italian expansionism as stipulated in the Treaty of London.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The treaty was largely disregarded by Britain and France because of conflicting promises made to Serbia and a perceived lack of Italian contribution to the war effort outside Italy itself.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The 1919 Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye did transfer the Austrian Littoral and Istria to Italy but awarded Dalmatia to Yugoslavia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the war, a private force of demobilized Italian soldiers seized Rijeka and set up the Italian Regency of Carnaro—seen as a harbinger of Fascism—in order to force the recognition of Italian claims to the city.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During World War II, the Adriatic saw only limited naval action, starting with the Italian invasion of Albania and the joint Axis invasion of Yugoslavia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The latter led to the annexation of a large part of Dalmatia and nearly all the eastern Adriatic islands by Italy and the establishment of two puppet states, the Independent State of Croatia and the Kingdom of Montenegro, which controlled the remainder of the former Yugoslav Adriatic coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1947, after the Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces and the war's end, Italy (now a republic) and the Allies signed the Treaty of Peace with Italy.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The FTT was partitioned in 1954: Trieste itself and the area to the North of it were placed under Italian control, while the rest came under Yugoslav control.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] This arrangement was made permanent in the 1975 Treaty of Osimo.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] During the Cold War, the Adriatic Sea became the southernmost flank of the Iron Curtain as Italy joined NATO, while the Warsaw Pact established bases in Albania.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] After the fall of communism, Yugoslavia broke apart: Slovenia and Croatia declared independence in 1991, and Bosnia–Herzegovina followed in 1992, while Montenegro remained in a federation with Serbia, officially called Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The ensuing Croatian War of Independence included limited naval engagements and a blockade of Croatia's coast by the Yugoslav Navy, leading to the Battle of the Dalmatian channels and a later withdrawal of Yugoslav vessels.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Montenegro declared itself independent in 2006, effectively land-locking Serbia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The period also saw the Adriatic Sea as the theatre of several NATO operations, including the blockade of Yugoslavia, intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina and the 1999 bombing of Yugoslavia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Italy and Yugoslavia defined their Adriatic continental shelf delimitation in 1968, with an additional agreement signed in 1975 on the Gulf of Trieste boundary, following the Treaty of Osimo.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The boundary agreed in 1968 extends 353 nautical miles (654 km; 406 mi) and consists of 43 points connected by straight lines or circular arc segments.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The additional boundary agreed upon in 1975 consists of 5 points, extending from an end point of the 1968 line.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] All successor states of former Yugoslavia accepted the agreements.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Adriatic's southernmost areas the border was not determined in order to avoid prejudicing the location of the tripoint with the Albanian continental shelf border, which remains undefined.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Before the breakup of Yugoslavia, Albania, Italy and Yugoslavia initially proclaimed 15-nautical-mile (28 km; 17 mi) territorial waters, subsequently reduced to international-standard 12 nautical miles (22 km; 14 mi) and all sides adopted baseline systems (mostly in the 1970s).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Albania and Italy determined their sea border in 1992 according to the equidistance principle.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Following Croatian EU membership, the Adriatic became an internal sea of the EU.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea defines the Adriatic Sea as an enclosed or semi-enclosed sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Euroregion was established in Pula in 2006 to promote trans-regional and trans-national cooperation in the Adriatic Sea area and serve as an Adriatic framework to help resolve issues of regional importance.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In addition, the maritime boundary between Albania and Montenegro was not defined before the 1990s.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia and Slovenia started negotiations to define maritime borders in the Gulf of Piran in 1992 but failed to agree, resulting in a dispute.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Both countries also declared their economic zones, which partially overlap.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia's application to become an EU member state was initially suspended pending resolution of its border disputes with Slovenia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] These disputes with Slovenia were eventually settled with an agreement to accept the decision of an international arbitration commission set up via the UN, enabling Croatia to progress towards EU membership.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia is still not following the resolution of the international arbitration for the Gulf of Piran.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] A dispute over the gulf is still on going with the Croatians handing out fines to Slovenian fishermen that are following the agreed economic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Aside from the EU membership difficulty, even before its settling the dispute has caused no major practical problems.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The maritime boundary between Bosnia–Herzegovina and Croatia was formally settled in 1999, but a few issues are still in dispute—the Klek peninsula and two islets in the border area.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Croatia–Montenegro maritime boundary is disputed in the Bay of Kotor, at the Prevlaka peninsula.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] This dispute was exacerbated by the peninsula's occupation by the Yugoslav People's Army and later by the (Serbian–Montenegrin) FR Yugoslav Army, which in turn was replaced by a United Nations observer mission that lasted until 2002.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia took over the area with an agreement that allowed Montenegrin presence in the bay's Croatian waters, and the dispute has become far less contentious since Montenegro's independence in 2006.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Sea fishery's production is distributed among countries in the basin.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2000, the nominal—on a live weight basis—total landings of all Adriatic fisheries reached 110,000 tonnes (108,000 long tons).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Overfishing is a recognised problem—450 species of fish live in the Adriatic Sea, including 120 species threatened by excessive commercial fishing, a problem exacerbated by pollution and global warming.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Overexploited species include common dentex, red scorpionfish, monkfish, John Dory, blue shark, spiny dogfish, mullet, red mullet, Norway lobster, as well as European hake, and sardines.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Turtles and common bottlenose dolphins are also being killed by fishing nets.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The depleted fish stock, and Croatia's Ecological and Fisheries Protection Zone (ZERP) contributed to accusations of overfishing exchanged between Italian and Croatian fishermen.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] ZERP was introduced in 2003, but its application to EU member states was suspended in 2004.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The depleted stocks of fish are being addressed through a new proposed EU fisheries policy that was scheduled to take effect in 2013, when Croatia acceded to the EU, and restore the stocks to sustainable levels by 2015.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest volume of fish harvesting was in Italy, where the total production volume in 2007 stood at 465,637 tonnes (458,283 long tons).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2003, 28.8% of Italian fisheries production volume was generated in the Northern and central Adriatic, and 24.5% in Apulia (from the Southern Adriatic and Ionian Sea).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Italian fisheries, including those operating outside the Adriatic, employed 60,700 in the primary sector, including aquaculture (which comprises 40% of the total fisheries production).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The total fisheries output's gross value in 2002 was $1.9 billion.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, Croatia's production in live weight reached 53,083 tonnes (52,245 long tons).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2006, the total Croatian fisheries production volume was 37,800 tonnes (37,200 long tons) of catch and 14,200 tonnes (14,000 long tons) from marine aquaculture.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatian fisheries employed approximately 20,000.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatian marine aquaculture production consisted of tuna (47.2%), oysters and mussels (28.2% combined) and bass and bream (24.6% combined).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, Albanian fisheries production amounted to 7,505 tonnes (7,386 long tons), including aquaculture production, which reached 1,970 tonnes (1,940 long tons) in 2006.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] At the same time, Slovenian fisheries produced a total of 2,500 tonnes (2,460 long tons) with 55% of the production volume originating in aquaculture, representing the highest ratio in the Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Finally, the Montenegrin fisheries production stood at 911 tonnes (897 long tons) in 2006, with only 11 tonnes coming from aquaculture.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, the fisheries production in Bosnia–Herzegovina reached volume of 9,625 and 2,463 tonnes (9,473 and 2,424 long tons) in Slovenia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The countries bordering the Adriatic Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest number of tourist overnight stays and the most numerous tourist accommodation facilities are recorded in Italy, especially in the Veneto region (around Venice).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Veneto is followed by the Emilia-Romagna region and by the Adriatic Croatian counties.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Croatian tourist facilities are further augmented by 21,000 nautical ports and moorings; nautical tourists are attracted to various types of marine protected areas.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] As of January 2012, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 103 Italian Adriatic beaches and 29 marinas, 116 Croatian beaches and 19 marinas, 7 Slovenian beaches and 2 marinas, and 16 Montenegrin beaches.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Adriatic tourism is a significant source of income for these countries, especially in Croatia and Montenegro where the tourism income generated along the Adriatic coast represents the bulk of such income.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The direct contribution of travel and tourism to Croatia's GDP stood at 5.1% in 2011, with the total industry contribution estimated at 12.8% of the national GDP.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] For Montenegro, the direct contribution of tourism to the national GDP is 8.1%, with the total contribution to the economy at 17.2% of Montenegrin GDP.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Tourism in Adriatic Croatia has recently exhibited greater growth than in the other regions around the Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] There are nineteen Adriatic Sea ports (in four different countries) that each handles more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest cargo ports among them are the Port of Trieste (the largest Adriatic cargo port in Italy), the Port of Venice, the Port of Ravenna, the Port of Koper (the largest Slovenian port), the Port of Rijeka (the largest Croatian cargo port), and the Port of Brindisi.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest passenger ports in the Adriatic are the Port of Split (the largest Croatian passenger port) and ports in Ancona (the largest Italian passenger seaport in the Adriatic).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest seaport in Montenegro is the Port of Bar.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2010, the Northern Adriatic seaports of Trieste, Venice, Ravenna, Koper and Rijeka founded the North Adriatic Ports Association to position themselves more favourably in the EU's transport systems.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The port of Trieste is of particular importance for Central Europe because this is where the Transalpine Pipeline begins, supplying 100 percent of southern Germany, 90 percent of Austria and 50 percent of the Czech Republic with crude oil.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Natural gas is produced through several projects, including a joint venture of the Eni and INA companies that operates two platforms—one is in Croatian waters and draws gas from six wells, and the other (which started operating in 2010) is located in Italian waters.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic gas fields were discovered in the 1970s, but their development commenced in 1996.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2008, INA produced 14.58 million BOE per day of gas.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] About 100 offshore platforms are located in the Emilia-Romagna region, along with 17 in the Northern Adriatic.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Eni estimated its concessions in the Adriatic Sea to hold at least 40,000,000,000 cubic metres (1.4×1012 cu ft) of natural gas, adding that they may even reach 100,000,000,000 cubic metres (3.5×1012 cu ft).
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] INA estimates, however, are 50% lower than those supplied by Eni.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Oil was discovered in the Northern Adriatic at a depth of approximately 5,400 metres (17,700 ft); the discovery was assessed as not viable because of its location, depth and quality.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] These gas and oil reserves are part of the Po basin Province of Northern Italy and the Northern Mediterranean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In the 2000s, investigation works aimed at discovering gas and oil reserves in the Middle and Southern Adriatic basins intensified, and by the decade's end, oil and natural gas reserves were discovered southeast of the Bari, Brindisi—Rovesti and Giove oil discoveries.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Surveys indicate reserves of 3 billion barrels of oil in place and 5.7×1010 cubic metres (2,000,000,000,000 cu ft) of gas in place.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] The discovery was followed by further surveys off the Croatian coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] In January 2012, INA commenced prospecting for oil off Dubrovnik, marking the resumption of oil exploration along the eastern Adriatic coast after surveys commenced in the late 1980s around the island of Brač were cancelled because of Yugoslavia's breakup and war in Croatia.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] Montenegro is also expected to look for oil off its coast.
[src:bering-sea/adriatic-sea-p02] As of January 2012, only 200 exploration wells had been sunk off the Croatian coast, with all but 30 in the Northern Adriatic basin.
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] The name was recorded in 1840 by Ivan Veniaminov.
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] It may arise from the word "Adudak", which means "somewhat long".
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] The island about 1.2 miles (2 km) long and is located 5.0 miles (8 km) off the northwest coast of Umnak Island.
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] It reaches an elevation of about 102 feet (31 m) above sea level and the area around the island is extremely hazardous to ships because of the numerous rocks that lie just below the surface of the water.
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] The island has been protected as a rookery for the endangered Steller sea lion, which has been observed during the winter feeding on the fish that inhabit the water nearby.
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] Cassin's auklet once lived in the area, but disappeared.
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] They also disappeared from other Aleutian islands such as Keegaloo, and Ilak Island due to introduced predators, oil spills, and mortality from fisheries interactions.
[src:bering-sea/adugak-island] Some animals on the island were tested positive for Polydnavirus, along with Yunaska.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The **Aegean Sea** is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea between Europe and Asia.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] It is located between the Balkans and Anatolia, and covers an area of some 215,000 km2 (83,000 sq mi).
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In the north, the Aegean is connected to the Marmara Sea, which in turn connects to the Black Sea, by the straits of the Dardanelles and the Bosphorus, respectively.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are located within the sea and some bound it on its southern periphery, including Crete and Rhodes.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The sea reaches a maximum depth of 2,639 m (8,658 ft) to the west of Karpathos.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Thracian Sea and the Sea of Crete are main subdivisions of the Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands can be divided into several island groups, including the Dodecanese, the Cyclades, the Sporades, the Saronic islands and the North Aegean Islands, as well as Crete and its surrounding islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Dodecanese, located to the southeast, includes the islands of Rhodes, Kos, and Patmos; the islands of Delos and Naxos are within the Cyclades to the south of the sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Lesbos is part of the North Aegean Islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Euboea, the second-largest island in Greece, is located in the Aegean, despite being administered as part of Central Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Nine out of twelve of the Administrative regions of Greece border the sea, along with the Turkish provinces of Edirne, Çanakkale, Balıkesir, İzmir, Aydın and Muğla to the east of the sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Various Turkish islands in the sea are Imbros, Tenedos, Cunda Island, and the Foça Islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea has been historically important, especially regarding the civilization of Ancient Greece, which inhabited the area around the coast of the Aegean and the Aegean islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands facilitated contact between the people of the area and between Europe and Asia.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Along with the Greeks, Thracians lived along the northern coasts.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Romans conquered the area under the Roman Empire, and later the Byzantine Empire held it against advances by the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Fourth Crusade weakened Byzantine control of the area, and it was eventually conquered by the Ottoman Empire, with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onwards.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The rocks making up the floor of the Aegean are mainly limestone, though often greatly altered by volcanic activity that has convulsed the region in relatively recent geologic times.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Of particular interest are the richly colored sediments in the region of the islands of Santorini and Milos, in the south Aegean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Notable cities on the Aegean coastline include Athens, Thessaloniki, Heraklion, Volos, Alexandroupolis and Kavala in Greece, and İzmir and Bodrum in Turkey.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Several issues concerning sovereignty within the Aegean Sea are disputed between Greece and Turkey.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean dispute has had a large effect on Greece-Turkey relations since the 1970s.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Issues include the delimitation of territorial waters, national airspace, exclusive economic zones, and flight information regions.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Ancient Greek authors also called it the "Greek Sea".
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The sea was known in Latin as *Mare Aegaeum* while under the control of the Roman Empire.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Pliny the Elder write that the Romans used the terms "Macedonian" for the northern part near Macedonia and Thrace provinces, and "Grecian" for the part near Greece itself.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In medieval Latin, the Aegean Sea was known as *Egeopelagus*, a form attested as late as 1419 in Venetian state papers (Ducatus Egeopelagi) and derived from the Greek αἰγαιοπέλαγος / αἰγαῖον πέλαγος.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The term *Arcipelago* also appears, for instance in a treaty on 30 June 1268 between the Venetians and the emperor Michael Palaeologus.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] This term subsequently gave rise to *Archipelago* (Greek: αρχιπέλαγος), which in many European languages originally referred specifically to the Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The terms *Greek Archipelago* or *Grecian Archipelago* were also used.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Later, as archipelago came to be used increasingly as a generic term for island-studded seas, the terms Greek Archipelago or Grecian Archipelago continued to be used alongside the ancient name, Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In some South Slavic languages, the Aegean is called *White Sea* (Bulgarian: Бяло море, romanized: *Byalo more*; Macedonian: Бело море, romanized: *Belo more*; Serbian: *Belo more* / Бело море).
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Turkish name for the sea is *Ege Denizi*, which is derived from the Greek name, and *Adalar Denizi* meaning "Sea of Islands".
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In the past, Turks also referred to it as the "White Sea", to differentiate it from the Black Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is an elongated embayment of the Mediterranean Sea and covers about 214,000 square kilometres (83,000 sq mi) in area, measuring about 670 kilometres (420 mi) longitudinally and 390 kilometres (240 mi) latitudinal.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The sea's maximum depth is 2,639 metres (8,658 ft), located at a point west of Karpathos.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Islands are found within its waters, with the following islands delimiting the sea on the south, generally from west to east: Kythera, Antikythera, Crete, Kasos, Karpathos and Rhodes.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Anatolian peninsula marks the eastern boundary of the sea, while the Greek mainland marks the west.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Several seas are contained within the Aegean Sea; the Thracian Sea is a section of the Aegean located to the north, the Icarian Sea to the east, the Myrtoan Sea to the west, while the Sea of Crete is the southern section.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Greek regions that border the sea, in alphabetical order, are Attica, Central Greece, Central Macedonia, Crete, Eastern Macedonia and Thrace, North Aegean, Peloponnese, South Aegean, and Thessaly.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The traditional Greek region of Macedonia also borders the sea, to the north.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Many of the Aegean islands or island chains, are geographical extensions of the mountains on the mainland.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] One chain extends across the sea to Chios, another extends across Euboea to Samos, and a third extends across the Peloponnese and Crete to Rhodes, dividing the Aegean from the Mediterranean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea is connected to the Sea of Marmara by the Dardanelles, also known from Classical Antiquity as the Hellespont.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles are located to the northeast of the sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] It ultimately connects with the Black Sea through the Bosporus strait, upon which lies the city of Istanbul.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Dardanelles and the Bosporus are known as the Turkish Straits.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Aegean surface water circulates in a counterclockwise gyre, with hypersaline Mediterranean water moving northward along the west coast of Turkey, before being displaced by less dense Black Sea outflow.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The dense Mediterranean water sinks below the Black Sea inflow to a depth of 23–30 metres (75–98 ft), then flows through the Dardanelles Strait and into the Sea of Marmara at velocities of 5–15 cm/s (2–6 in/s).
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Black Sea outflow moves westward along the northern Aegean Sea, then flows southwards along the east coast of Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The physical oceanography of the Aegean Sea is controlled mainly by the regional climate, the fresh water discharge from major rivers draining southeastern Europe, and the seasonal variations in the Black Sea surface water outflow through the Dardanelles Strait.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The climate of the Aegean Sea largely reflects the climate of Greece and Western Turkey, which is to say, predominantly Mediterranean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] According to the Köppen climate classification, most of the Aegean is classified as Hot-summer Mediterranean (*Csa*), with hotter and drier summers along with milder and wetter winters.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] However, high temperatures during summers are generally not quite as high as those in arid or semiarid climates due to the presence of a large body of water.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] This is most predominant in the west and east coasts of the Aegean, and within the Aegean islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In the north of the Aegean Sea, the climate is instead classified as Cold semi-arid *(BSk)*, which feature cooler summers than Hot-summer Mediterranean climates.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Etesian winds are a dominant weather influence in the Aegean Basin.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Numerous Greek and Turkish settlements are located along their mainland coast, as well as on towns on the Aegean islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The largest cities are Athens and Thessaloniki in Greece and İzmir in Turkey.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The most populated of the Aegean islands is Crete, followed by Euboea and Rhodes.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Greece has established several marine protected areas along its coasts.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] According to the Network of Managers of Marine Protected Areas in the Mediterranean (MedPAN), four Greek MPAs are participating in the Network.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] These include Alonnisos Marine Park, while the Missolonghi–Aitoliko Lagoons and the island of Zakynthos are not on the Aegean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The current coastline dates back to about 4000 BC.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Before that time, at the peak of the last ice age (about 18,000 years ago) sea levels everywhere were 130 metres (430 ft) lower, and there were large well-watered coastal plains instead of much of the northern Aegean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] When they were first occupied, the present-day islands including Milos with its important obsidian production were probably still connected to the mainland.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The present coastal arrangement appeared around 9,000 years ago, with post-ice age sea levels continuing to rise for another 3,000 years after that.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The subsequent Bronze Age civilizations of Greece and the Aegean Sea have given rise to the general term *Aegean civilization*.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In ancient times, the sea was the birthplace of two ancient civilizations – the Minoans of Crete and the Mycenaeans of the Peloponnese.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Minoan civilization was a Bronze Age civilization on the island of Crete and other Aegean islands, flourishing from around 3000 to 1450 BC before a period of decline, finally ending at around 1100 BC.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] It represented the first advanced civilization in Europe, leaving behind massive building complexes, tools, stunning artwork, writing systems, and a massive network of trade.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Minoan period saw extensive trade between Crete, Aegean, and Mediterranean settlements, particularly the Near East.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The most notable Minoan palace is that of Knossos, followed by that of Phaistos.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Mycenaean Greeks arose on the mainland, becoming the first advanced civilization in mainland Greece, which lasted from approximately 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] It is believed that the site of Mycenae, which sits close to the Aegean coast, was the center of Mycenaean civilization.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Mycenaeans introduced several innovations in the fields of engineering, architecture and military infrastructure, while trade over vast areas of the Mediterranean, including the Aegean, was essential for the Mycenaean economy.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Their syllabic script, the Linear B, offers the first written records of the Greek language and their religion already included several deities that can also be found in the Olympic Pantheon.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Mycenaean Greece was dominated by a warrior elite society and consisted of a network of palace-centered states that developed rigid hierarchical, political, social and economic systems.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] At the head of this society was the king, known as *wanax*.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The civilization of Mycenaean Greeks perished with the collapse of Bronze Age culture in the eastern Mediterranean, to be followed by the so-called Greek Dark Ages.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] It is undetermined what cause the collapse of the Mycenaeans.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] During the Greek Dark Ages, writing in the Linear B script ceased, vital trade links were lost, and towns and villages were abandoned.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Archaic period followed the Greek Dark Ages in the 8th century BC.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Greece became divided into small self-governing communities, and adopted the Phoenician alphabet, modifying it to create the Greek alphabet.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] By the 6th century BC several cities had emerged as dominant in Greek affairs: Athens, Sparta, Corinth, and Thebes, of which Athens, Sparta, and Corinth were closest to the Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Each of them had brought the surrounding rural areas and smaller towns under their control, and Athens and Corinth had become major maritime and mercantile powers as well.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In the 8th and 7th centuries BC many Greeks migrated to form colonies in Magna Graecia (Southern Italy and Sicily), Asia Minor and further afield.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea was the setting for one of the most pivotal naval engagements in history, when, on 20 September 480 B.C., the Athenian fleet gained a decisive victory over the Persian fleet of the Xerxes II of Persia at the Battle of Salamis.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Thus ending any further attempt of western expansion by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean Sea would later come to be under the control, albeit briefly, of the Kingdom of Macedonia.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Philip II and his son Alexander the Great led a series of conquests that led not only to the unification of the Greek mainland and the control of the Aegean Sea under his rule, but also the destruction of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] After Alexander the Great's death, his empire was divided among his generals.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Cassander became king of the Hellenistic kingdom of Macedon, which held territory along the western coast of the Aegean, roughly corresponding to modern-day Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Kingdom of Lysimachus had control over the sea's eastern coast.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Greece had entered the Hellenistic period.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Macedonian Wars were a series of conflicts fought by the Roman Republic and its Greek allies in the eastern Mediterranean against several different major Greek kingdoms.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] They resulted in Roman control or influence over the eastern Mediterranean basin, including the Aegean, in addition to their hegemony in the western Mediterranean after the Punic Wars.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] During Roman rule, the land around the Aegean Sea fell under the provinces of Achaea, Macedonia, Thracia, Asia and Creta et Cyrenaica (island of Crete).
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The fall of the Western Roman Empire allowed its successor state, the Byzantine Empire, to continue Roman control over the Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] However, their territory would later be threatened by the early Muslim conquests initiated by Muhammad in the 7th century.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Although the Rashidun Caliphate did not manage to obtain land along the coast of the Aegean Sea, its conquest of the Eastern Anatolian peninsula as well as Egypt, the Levant, and North Africa left the Byzantine Empire weakened.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Umayyad Caliphate expanded the territorial gains of the Rashidun Caliphate, conquering much of North Africa, and threatened the Byzantine Empire's control of Western Anatolia, where it meets the Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] During the 820s, Crete was conquered by a group of Berbers Andalusians exiles led by Abu Hafs Umar al-Iqritishi, and it became an independent Islamic state.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Byzantine Empire launched a campaign that took most of the island back in 842 and 843 under Theoktistos, but the re-conquest was not completed and was soon reversed.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Later attempts by the Byzantine Empire to recover the island were without success.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] For the approximately 135 years of its existence, the emirate of Crete was one of the major foes of Byzantium.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Crete commanded the sea lanes of the Eastern Mediterranean and functioned as a forward base and haven for Muslim corsair fleets that ravaged the Byzantine-controlled shores of the Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Crete returned to Byzantine rule under Nikephoros II Phokas, who launched a huge campaign against the Emirate of Crete in 960 to 961.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Meanwhile, the Bulgarian Empire threatened Byzantine control of Northern Greece and the Aegean coast to the south.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Under Presian and his successor Boris I, the Bulgarian Empire managed to obtain a small portion of the northern Aegean coast.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Simeon I of Bulgaria led Bulgaria to its greatest territorial expansion, and managed to conqueror much of the northern and western coasts of the Aegean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Second Bulgarian Empire achieved similar success along, again, the northern and western coasts, under Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Seljuk Turks, under the Seljuk Empire, invaded the Byzantine Empire in 1068, from which they annexed almost all the territories of Anatolia, including the east coast of the Aegean Sea, during the reign of Alp Arslan, the second Sultan of the Seljuk Empire.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] After the death of his successor, Malik Shah I, the empire was divided, and Malik Shah was succeeded in Anatolia by Kilij Arslan I, who founded the Sultanate of Rum.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Byzantines yet again recaptured the eastern coast of the Aegean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Venetians created the maritime state of the Duchy of the Archipelago, which included all the Cyclades except Mykonos and Tinos.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Empire of Nicaea, a Byzantine rump state, managed to affect the Recapture of Constantinople from the Latins in 1261 and defeat Epirus.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Byzantine successes were not to last; the Ottomans would conquer the area around the Aegean coast, but before their expansion the Byzantine Empire had already been weakened from internal conflict.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] By the late 14th century, the Byzantine Empire had lost all control of the coast of the Aegean Sea and could only exercise power around their capital, Constantinople.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire then gained control of all the Aegean coast with the exception of Crete, which was a Venetian colony until 1669.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Greek War of Independence allowed a Greek state on the coast of the Aegean from 1829 onward.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In the aftermath of the Balkan Wars (1912–1913) Greece expanded northwards along the coast, while Bulgaria gained access in the northernmost section of the sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Ottoman Empire held a presence over the sea for over 500 years until its dissolution following World War I, when it was replaced by modern Turkey.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] After the war, Greece gained control over the area around the northern coast of the Aegean, including the territory held by Bulgaria.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] By the 1920s, Greece and Turkey had about resumed their present-day borders.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In the Italo-Turkish War of 1912, Italy captured the Dodecanese islands, and had occupied them since, reneging on the 1919 Venizelos–Tittoni agreement to cede them to Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Greco-Italian War took place from October 1940 to April 1941 as part of the Balkans Campaign of World War II.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Italian war aim was to establish a Greek puppet state, which would permit the Italian annexation of the Sporades and Cyclades islands in the Aegean Sea, to be administered as a part of the Italian Aegean Islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The German invasion resulted in the Axis occupation of Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The German troops evacuated Athens on 12 October 1944, and by the end of the month, they had withdrawn from mainland Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Greece was then liberated by Allied troops.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Many of the islands in the Aegean have safe harbours and bays.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In ancient times, navigation through the sea was easier than travelling across the rough terrain of the Greek mainland, and to some extent, the coastal areas of Anatolia.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Many of the islands are volcanic, and marble and iron are mined on other islands.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The larger islands have some fertile valleys and plains.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Of the main islands in the Aegean Sea, two belong to Turkey – Bozcaada (Tenedos) and Gökçeada (Imbros); the rest belong to Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Between the two countries, there are political disputes over several aspects of political control over the Aegean space, including the size of territorial waters, air control and the delimitation of economic rights to the continental shelf.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] These issues are known as the Aegean dispute.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Multiple ports are located along the Greek and Turkish coasts of the Aegean Sea.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The port of Piraeus in Athens is the chief port in Greece, the largest passenger port in Europe and the third largest in the world, servicing about 20 million passengers annually.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] With a throughput of 1.4 million TEUs, Piraeus is placed among the top ten ports in container traffic in Europe and the top container port in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Piraeus is also the commercial hub of Greek shipping.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Piraeus bi-annually acts as the focus for a major shipping convention, known as Posidonia, which attracts maritime industry professionals from all over the world.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Piraeus is currently Greece's third-busiest port in terms of tons of goods transported, behind Agioi Theodoroi and Thessaloniki.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The central port serves ferry routes to almost every island in the eastern portion of Greece, the island of Crete, the Cyclades, the Dodecanese, and much of the northern and the eastern Aegean Sea, while the western part of the port is used for cargo services.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] As of 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki was the second-largest container port in Greece after the port of Piraeus, making it one of the busiest ports in Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] In 2007, the Port of Thessaloniki handled 14,373,245 tonnes of cargo and 222,824 TEU's.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Paloukia, on the island of Salamis, is a major passenger port.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Fish are Greece's second-largest agricultural export, and Greece has Europe's largest fishing fleet.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Fish captured include sardines, mackerel, grouper, grey mullets, sea bass, and seabream.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] There is a considerable difference between fish catches between the pelagic and demersal zones; with respect to pelagic fisheries, the catches from the northern, central and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated, respectively, by anchovy, horse mackerels, and boops.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] For demersal fisheries, the catches from the northern and southern Aegean area groupings are dominated by grey mullets and pickerel (*Spicara smaris*) respectively.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The industry has been impacted by the Great Recession.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Overfishing and habitat destruction is also a concern, threatening grouper, and seabream populations, resulting in perhaps a 50% decline of fish catch.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] To address these concerns, Greek fishermen have been offered a compensation by the government.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Although some species are defined as protected or threatened under EU legislation, several illegal species such as the molluscs *Pinna nobilis*, *Charonia tritonis* and *Lithophaga lithophaga*, can be bought in restaurants and fish markets around Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The Aegean islands within the Aegean Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Tourism to the Aegean islands contributes a significant portion of tourism in Greece, especially since the second half of the 20th century.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] A total of five UNESCO World Heritage sites are located the Aegean Islands; these include the Monastery of Saint John the Theologian and the Cave of the Apocalypse on Patmos, the Pythagoreion and Heraion of Samos in Samos, the Nea Moni of Chios, the island of Delos, and the Medieval City of Rhodes.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Greece is one of the most visited countries in Europe and the world with over 33 million visitors in 2018, and the tourism industry around a quarter of Greece's Gross Domestic Product.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The islands of Santorini, Crete, Lesbos, Delos, and Mykonos are common tourist destinations.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] An estimated 2 million tourists visit Santorini annually.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] However, concerns relating to overtourism have arisen in recent years, such as issues of inadequate infrastructure and overcrowding.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Alongside Greece, Turkey has also been successful in developing resort areas and attracting large number of tourists, contributing to tourism in Turkey.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The phrase "Blue Cruise" refers to recreational voyages along the Turkish Riviera, including across the Aegean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The ancient city of Troy, a World Heritage Site, is on the Turkish coast of the Aegean.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Greece and Turkey both take part in the Blue Flag beach certification programme of the Foundation for Environmental Education.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] The certification is awarded for beaches and marinas meeting strict quality standards including environmental protection, water quality, safety and services criteria.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] As of 2015, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 395 beaches and 9 marinas in Greece.
[src:bering-sea/aegean-sea] Southern Aegean beaches on the Turkish coast include Muğla, with 102 beaches awarded with the blue flag, along with İzmir and Aydın, who have 49 and 30 beaches awarded respectively.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Agattu has been recognised as an Important Bird Area (IBA) by BirdLife International.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] It has seven large seabird colonies, and an estimated population of 66,000 birds.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] About 1% of the global population of red-faced cormorants and tufted puffins nest on the island.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Other inhabitants include rock sandpiper, red-necked phalarope, grey-crowned rosy finch and snow bunting.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Aleutian cackling geese were reintroduced to the island after foxes were eliminated from the island in the 1970s.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] The elimination of the foxes on the island also made it possible for conservationists to reintroduce the Evermann's rock ptarmigan (*Lagopus muta evermanni*).
[src:bering-sea/agattu] In 2006 there were reports of at least 25 breeding pairs of the ptarmigan on the island.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Agattu is unique among the volcanic Aleutian Islands in being composed almost entirely of well-bedded sedimentary rocks.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] These rocks were clearly deposited in water and are composed chiefly of amorphous silica and fine detritus derived from a volcanic terrain.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Igneous rocks are sparsely represented by intrusions of porphyry, diabase, and trap.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] The entire island has been heavily glaciated.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Archeological excavations have discovered evidence and remains of Aleuts living on Agattu Island as early as 760 BCE.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Based on the number of simultaneously inhabited archeological sites on the island, experts have estimated that the pre-contact population may have reached 500–1000 individuals.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] After Russian contact with the Aleutians in 1751, the population on Agattu declined precipitously.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Russian traders would stay multiple years at a time in the Near islands hunting sea otter.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] Interactions with the Aleuts were sometimes violent.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] A veteran Russian navigator was killed by the locals on Agattu in 1761.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] By the 1760s, all Near Islanders had moved into a single village on Attu Island.
[src:bering-sea/agattu] During World War II, the villagers of Attu were interned in Japan and at war's end the survivors were resettled on Atka Island.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] The island lies east of Akutan Island and southwest of Unimak Island, across the Unimak Pass strait.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] The Krenitzin Islands lie to the south and southeast, across the Avatanak Strait.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] Akun Island has a land area of 64.39 sq mi (166.77 km²).
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] It is unpopulated, except for airport workers and a few people controlling the cattle.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] Akun Island is home to a small but significant population of cows.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] They are no longer domesticated but the population is controlled.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] Three domesticated horses also inhabit the island.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] With the cessation of amphibious airplane service to Akutan on Akutan Island, the Akutan Seaplane Base closed in 2012.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] It was replaced by a new $75.5m land-based airstrip six miles (9.7 km) across the water on Akun Island, named Akutan Airport.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] It was built by Kiewit, R&M Consultants, and DOT.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] The airport was connected to Akutan by an expensive hovercraft shuttle, which couldn't operate safely when winds were too strong or waves too high.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] A helicopter provides the link between Akun and Akutan.
[src:bering-sea/akun-island] The airport has a small hotel, which is used when a flight arrives and the hovercraft is unable to run.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The **Bering Sea** (/ˈbɛərɪŋ, ˈbɛrɪŋ/ *BAIR-ing, BERR-ing*, US also /ˈbɪərɪŋ/ *BEER-ing*; Russian: Бе́рингово мо́ре, romanized: *Béringovo móre*, IPA: [ˈbʲerʲɪnɡəvə ˈmorʲe]) is a marginal sea of the Northern Pacific Ocean.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] It forms, along with the Bering Strait, the divide between the two largest landmasses on Earth: Eurasia and the Americas.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] It comprises a deep water basin, which then rises through a narrow slope into the shallower water above the continental shelves.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea is named after Vitus Bering, a Danish-born Russian navigator, who, in 1728, was the first European to systematically explore it, sailing from the Pacific Ocean northward to the Arctic Ocean.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea is separated from the Gulf of Alaska by the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Bristol Bay is the portion of the Bering Sea between the Alaska Peninsula and Cape Newenham on mainland Southwest Alaska.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea ecosystem includes resources within the jurisdiction of the United States and Russia, as well as international waters in the middle of the sea (known as the "Donut Hole").
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The interaction between currents, sea ice, and weather makes for a vigorous and productive ecosystem.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Most scientists think that during the last glacial period, sea level was low enough to allow humans to migrate east on foot from Asia to North America across what is now the Bering Strait.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Other animals including megafauna migrated in both directions.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] This is commonly referred to as the "Bering land bridge" and is accepted by most, though not all scientists, to be the first point of entry of humans into the Americas.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] There is a small portion of the Kula plate in the Bering Sea.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Kula plate is an ancient tectonic plate that used to subduct under Alaska.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] On 18 December 2018, a large meteor exploded above the Bering Sea.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The meteor exploded at an altitude of 25.6km, releasing 49 kilotons of energy.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] in such a way that all the narrow waters between Alaska and Kamchatka are included in the Bering Sea.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea contains 16 submarine canyons including the largest submarine canyon in the world, Zhemchug Canyon.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea shelf break is the dominant driver of primary productivity in the Bering Sea.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] This zone, where the shallower continental shelf drops off into the North Aleutians Basin is also known as the "Greenbelt".
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Nutrient upwelling from the cold waters of the Aleutian basin flowing up the slope and mixing with shallower waters of the shelf provide for constant production of phytoplankton.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The second driver of productivity in the Bering Sea is seasonal sea ice that, in part, triggers the spring phytoplankton bloom.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Seasonal melting of sea ice causes an influx of lower salinity water into the middle and other shelf areas, causing stratification and hydrographic effects which influence productivity.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] In addition to the hydrographic and productivity influence of melting sea ice, the ice itself also provides an attachment substrate for the growth of algae as well as interstitial ice algae.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Some evidence suggests that great changes to the Bering Sea ecosystem have already occurred.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Warm water conditions in the summer of 1997 resulted in a massive bloom of low energy coccolithophorid phytoplankton (Stockwell et al.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] A long record of carbon isotopes, which is reflective of primary production trends of the Bering Sea, exists from historical samples of bowhead whale baleen.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Trends in carbon isotope ratios in whale baleen samples suggest that a 30–40% decline in average seasonal primary productivity has occurred over the last 50 years.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The implication is that the carrying capacity of the Bering Sea is much lower now than it has been in the past.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The sea supports many whale species, including the beluga, humpback whale, bowhead whale, gray whale and blue whale, the vulnerable sperm whale, and the endangered fin whale, sei whale and the rarest in the world, the North Pacific right whale.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Other marine mammals include walrus, Steller sea lion, northern fur seal, orca and polar bear.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea is very important to the seabirds of the world.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Over 30 species of seabirds and approximately 20 million individuals breed in the Bering Sea region.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Seabird species include tufted puffins, the endangered short-tailed albatross, spectacled eider, and red-legged kittiwakes.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Many of these species are unique to the area, which provides highly productive foraging habitat, particularly along the shelf edge and in other nutrient-rich upwelling regions, such as the Pribilof, Zhemchug, and Pervenets canyons.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea is also home to colonies of crested auklets, with upwards of a million individuals.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Two Bering Sea species, the Steller's sea cow (*Hydrodamalis gigas*) and spectacled cormorant (*Phalacrocorax perspicillatus*), are extinct because of overexploitation by man.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] In addition, a small subspecies of Canada goose, the Bering Canada goose (*Branta canadensis asiatica*) is extinct due to overhunting and the introduction of rats to their breeding islands.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea supports many species of fish, some of which support large and valuable commercial fisheries.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Commercial fish species include Pacific cod, several species of flatfish, sablefish, Pacific salmon, and Pacific herring.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Shellfish include red king crab and snow crab.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Fish biodiversity is high, and at least 419 species of fish have been reported from the Bering Sea.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea is world-renowned for its productive and profitable fisheries, such as king crab, opilio and tanner crabs, Bristol Bay salmon, pollock and other groundfish.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] These fisheries rely on the productivity of the Bering Sea via a complicated and little understood food web.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Commercial fishing is lucrative business in the Bering Sea, which is relied upon by the largest seafood companies in the world to produce fish and shellfish.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] On the U.S. side, commercial fisheries catch approximately $1 billion worth of seafood annually, while Russian Bering Sea fisheries are worth approximately $600 million annually.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The Bering Sea also serves as the central location of the Alaskan king crab and snow crab seasons, which are chronicled on the Discovery Channel television program *Deadliest Catch*.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Landings from Alaskan waters represents half the U.S. catch of fish and shellfish.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Because of the changes going on in the Arctic, the future evolution of the Bering Sea climate and ecosystem is uncertain.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] Between 1979 and 2012, the region experienced small growth in sea ice extent, standing in contrast to the substantial loss of summer sea ice in the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] 'The White Seal', one of many chapters on Rudyard Kipling's *The Jungle Book*, features the Bering Sea as the birthplace and homeland of Kotick, a rare white fur seal.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The film *Harbinger Down*, which was released on August 7, 2015, was about a group of grad students who booked passage on the crabbing boat Harbinger to study the effects of global warming on a pod of beluga whales in the Bering Sea.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] One of the central characters in the 1949 film *Down to the Sea in Ships* has the given name "Bering" due to having been born in a ship crossing the Bering Sea.
[src:bering-sea/bering-sea] The 2002 supernatural thriller, *Ghost Ship*, directed by Steve Beck, follows a marine salvage crew in the Bering Sea who discover the lost Italian ocean liner, *Antonia Graza* that disappeared in 1962.
